PM100D2 Powermeter SCPI Commands
None CAL DISP FORM INP MEAS SENS SOUR STAT SYST
V 1.0.5.58 generated 15 Oct 2025, 14:51:27

This is the description of the Thorlabs PM100D2 Series remote interface. This single channel handheld Powermeter can be remotely controlled using the SCPI (Standard Commands for Programmable Instruments) interface.

In 1975, the IEEE standardized a bus developed by Hewlett-Packard originally called HPIB (Hewlett-Packard Interface Bus), later changed to GPIB (General Purpose Interface Bus). The standard was called IEEE 488 (IEEE 488.1) and it defined mechanical aspects of the bus. The later IEEE 488.2 defined its protocol properties. What was missing were set of rules between the manufacturers on commands to control the instruments. Sometimes these varied even between different models from the same manufacturer.

In 1990 SCPI Consortium released the first SCPI standard as an additional layer for the IEEE-488.2 standard.

SCPI commands are ASCII strings, which are sent to instrument over the physical communication layer. They can perform:

  • Set operations, for example the *RST command (resetting the instrument).
  • Query operations, for example the *IDN? query (querying the instrument’s identification string).

Some SCPI commands exist as both set commands and query commands. An example is an Powermeter's averaging command SENS:AVER. You can set it with the SCPI command SENS:AVER 2, and also query its current value with the SENS:AVER?.

The format mentioned in this manual e.g.: SENSe#:AVERage[:COUNt] <pres> is called canonical form. Here are the most important rules to remember:

  • The parts within square brackets are not mandatory and can be left out.
  • All # within the command represent a suffix positive integer number starting at 1. If there is only one suffix you may skip it because default is applied internally. If there are two or more suffix it is mandatory to specify all.
  • The capital letter parts are mandatory; the small letters can be omitted. This is called short form. An example of the above command in the short form is SENS1:AVER 3. You can use either the short form, or the long form SENSE1:AVERAGE 3, but nothing in between, e.g. SENS1:AVERA 3.
  • The SCPI commands are case-insensitive. You can also use the short form sens1:aver 3 or or the long form sense1:average 3
  • Combine multiple commands into one string using selmicolon ';'. For example, a combined string of SENS1:AVER 3 and SENS1:CORR:WAV 850 is SENS1:AVER 3;CORR:WAV 850. Notice that the second command does not have the SENS1: part. The reason is, that the command tree path does not change within one string. If you want to reset the command tree path to the root, use the colon character at the beginning of the second command: SENS1:AVER 3;:SENS2:CORR:WAV 850.
  • Create query forms by adding a question mark, mostly to the end: SENS1:AVER? Sometimes there is an additional parameter placed after the question mark. There must be a space character between the question mark and the additional parameter. For example: SENS1:CORR:WAV? MIN

This SCPI command descriptions follow a standardized format to ensure clarity and completeness. Each command entry includes the following sections:

Measurement Systems

The PM100D2 supports 3 different measurement systems and two different measurement modes. The following section provides a detailed description of these systems. Not all systems are supported by all sensors or operating modes.

CW vs Peak mode

The PM100D2 supports two different measurement modes in general. In CW mode the discrete input signal is sampled fixed at 100 kHz. Every millisecond the device processes the last 100 sample results. In CW mode the device outputs a constant measurement result stream regardless of input signal. This mode is supported for Photodiodes or Thermopiles.

In Peak mode the PM100D2 internally samples the signal at 400 kHz and searches for peaks in the digitalized input data. Only peak values and their relative timestamp are forwarded to the calculation process. In peak mode, the measurement stream output rate depends on the input signal repetition rate. If there are no peaks in input signal or the Powermeter is not configured appropriately no peaks are detected and there are no results to query. This mode is supported for Photodiode and Pyroelectric sensors only.

The Peak mode supports an overshoot filter for modulated signals. Use the command SENSe#:PEAKdetector:FILTer to enable/disable the overshoot filter. For sinus or triangle shaped signals disable the filter. It should be used for rectangular shaped signals where the flat top should be detected as peak and not the possible overshoot of the rising edge.

Slow Measurement System

The "Slow Measurement System" is available for all sensor types and measurement modes. It returns values up to a frequency of 1 kHz. The command SENS:AVER can be used to scale down the update rate by formula MeasFreq = 1000 / AVG in CW mode. In Peak mode the averaging is not used. Averaging is considered for the following units only:

  • POW: Photodiode/Thermopile: Sensor power in W or dBm (See command SENSe:POWer:UNIT)
  • CURR: Photodiode: Sensor current in Ampere
  • VOLT: Thermopile: Sensor voltage in Volt
  • PDEN: Photodiode: Sensor power density in W/cm²

All other units have their own independent update rate.

In peak mode the output depends on the repetition rate of the input signal. For repetition rates larger than 1 kHz, all peaks within the recent millisecond will get averaged.

The SCPI commands for this measurement system are part of the MEAS group. This group contains some convenience commands. These commands internally call a predefined SCPI command sequence. Starting with the well-known MEAS? convenience command:

  1. ABOR
    Aborts any ongoing measurement
  2. CONF
    Configures measurement channel for power measurement
  3. INIT
    Starts a new measurement
  4. FETC?
    Blocks until measurement is complete and returns the result

If the same unit should be read multiple times in a row, reconfiguring the channel again and again is not necessary. Therefore, use the READ? convenience command instead:

  1. ABOR
    Aborts any ongoing measurement
  2. INIT
    Starts a new measurement
  3. FETC?
    Blocks until measurement is complete and returns the result

The following diagram shows two examples of SCPI command sequences for the Slow Measurement System. There is no timing constraint between the single SCPI commands. Timeline is from left to right.

The first example shows a 1 kHz measurement scenario with an averaging of first INIT starts a new measurement. Once the measurement is complete, the result is stored internally until FETC? is called. If FETC? is called multiple times in a row the same result will be returned as no new measurement has been started.

The second example shows a 500 Hz measurement scenario with an averaging of second INIT starts the new measurement. Before the measurement result is ready FETC? is already called. As the measurement is still ongoing in the background the FETC? blocks the entire remote interface until measurement has been taken.

Once you send a FETC?, MEAS? or READ? command, the interface is blocked until the measurement has been taken. For Photodiode in CW mode and Thermopile sensors these commands work reliable except for very high averaging. High averaging values result in a long block time when waiting for the measurement to terminate. Continue reading to get a solution for this special case.

For Photodiode sensors in Peak mode the blocking of FETC?, MEAS? or READ? might be a problem. For constant pulse repetition rates > 0.5 Hz the commands work reliable. But when working with low pulse rates or even single pulse signals it is very likely to end up in a communication timeout of the USB or bluetooth interface. The following time diagram shows the problem. Note: the timeout of 3 seconds is just an example here.

The PM100D2 internally blocks 10 seconds before the internal FETC? function terminates. Within this time do not send an ABOR or any other SCPI command. Please do not enlarge the communication interface timeout to solve this problem but continue reading.

The lower part of the diagram shows the command sequence to use for one of the following cases:

  • Photodiode, Thermopile: AVG > 2000
  • Photodiode in Peak mode: Slow pulse repetition rates < 0.5 Hz
  • Photodiode in Peak mode: Single pulsed signals

Continous Measurements

The Slow Measurement System utilizes an internal queue to buffer one or multiple measurement results. This fixed-length queue is limited to 10 entries. Sending an ABOR command flushes the contents of the queue. If you invoke INIT, you can add a new single measurement to the queue. Additionally, you can use INIT:CONT to continuously add new entries to the queue. If there are one or more entries in the queue, FETC:STAT? will return 1. If the queue is full, you cannot add more data, and any new measurement results will be discarded. You can use FETC:ARR:LEN? to query the number of measurement results currently in the queue. The FETC? command will return the oldest entry in the queue and remove it from the queue. After that, you can use the single result or one of the array fetch commands. For more details about the fetch commands, please continue reading. All samples are stored with a relative wrapping microsecond timestamp indicating when the samples were taken.

The following command sequence shows how to use the Slow Measurement System for continuous measurements

  1. ABOR
    Flushes the queue content
  2. CONF:POW
    Configure for power measurement.
  3. CONF:POW:AVG 20
    Configure with averaging 20.
  4. INIT:CONT
    Starts a new measurement. Adds the result to the queue.
  5. FETC:STAT?
    Measurement ready? No wait a little and retry
  6. FETC:STAT?
    Measurement ready? Yes
  7. FETC?
    Query latest measurement result from queue.
  8. FETC:STAT?
    Measurement ready? Yes
  9. FETC?
    Query latest measurement result from queue.
  10. FETC:STAT?
    Measurement ready? Yes
  11. FETC?
    Query latest measurement result from queue.
  12. ...

The following command sequence shows how to use the Slow Measurement System for multiple single measurements

  1. ABOR
    Flushes the queue content
  2. CONF:POW
    Configure for power measurement.
  3. CONF:POW:AVG 1
    Configure with averaging 1.
  4. INIT
    Starts a new single measurement. Store in the queue.
  5. INIT
    Starts a new single measurement. Store in the queue.
  6. INIT
    Starts a new single measurement. Store in the queue.
  7. INIT
    Starts a new single measurement. Store in the queue.
  8. FETC:ARR:LEN?
    Query amount of entries in the queue.
  9. FETC? 0, 10, 1
    Query latest measurement result from queue including timestamp.
  10. FETC? 0, 10, 1
    Query latest measurement result from queue including timestamp.
  11. FETC? 0, 10, 1
    Query latest measurement result from queue including timestamp.
  12. FETC? 0, 10, 1
    Query latest measurement result from queue including timestamp.

Measurement fetching text or binary

Measurement results in the Slow Measurement System are stored in the device's internal queue. To retrieve the entries from the queue, use one of the four FETC? commands. Generally, there are SCPI-compliant text-based commands and their faster binary counterparts.

FETC? returns the oldest measurement result from the queue. You can utilize the three optional parameters to control the output. The first index is only applicable for the Scope Mode. The second timeout specifies how long the device should wait for a new measurement result. If it is less than 3 seconds, the command will block until the timeout and will return 0 if no measurement has been taken. For longer timeouts, an error will be queued to the SCPI error queue in case of a timeout (default behavior). The final optional parameter is a bitmask. If bit 0 is set to 1, the command will return a tuple with a relative timestamp in microseconds followed by the measurement value. If the bit is 0, the result will not include the timestamp (default). For closer details how to calcualte time delta between the samples read timebase section carefully.

FETC:ARR:TEXT? 0 returns one or multiple measurement results from the queue, starting with the oldest in text representation. You can use the two parameters to control the output. The first mandatory offset parameter is only relevant for the Scope Mode. The second mandatory parameter specifies the maximum number of results to query. The maximum length is limited to 10 entries. Please check the result to determine the number of entries actually fetched. If there are no results to query, you will receive a 0-length result without an error. The final optional parameter is a bitmask. If bit 0 is set to 1, the command will return a tuple with a relative timestamp in microseconds followed by the measurement value. If the bit is 0, the result will not include the timestamp (default).

FETC:BIN? returns the oldest measurement result from the queue in binary representation. The command operates exactly the same as the text FETC? version. It uses the same optional parameters. If the bitmask specifies to return with a timestamp, the results will start with a 4-byte unsigned integer value (starting LSB first) followed by an IEEE-compliant 4-byte float (also starting LSB first). For closer details read section binary data format.

FETC:ARR?is the binary version of the FETC:ARR:TEXT? equivalent. It uses the same parameters. The result begins with a 4-byte unsigned integer indicating the number of binary tuples that follow. Each tuple starts with a 4-byte unsigned integer (LSB first) followed by an IEEE-compliant 4-byte float. Therefore, each tuple is 8 bytes in total. To read the binary fetch array result, start by reading 4 bytes to obtain the number of pending tuples. Then, multiply this amount by 8 and read the payload bytes. For closer details read section binary data format.

There are some siedenotes to the queue and measurement result fetching. The queue length may differ for different units. You can use FETC:ARR:LEN? 1 to get the maximal amount of entries in the list.

Relative Timebase

To calculate the time delta between measurements a relative wrapping unsigned 32-bit microsecond counter is used. This timestamp is relative and is not a wall time. When calculating the time delta, integer wrapping must be considered. The following example demonstrates the special case. Time delta is 10 microseconds here.

4294967282, 0.0001233
4294967292, 0.0001265
                  6, 0.0001274
                16, 0.0001254

Use the following pseudo code to calculate the delta in Python:

if sample[n+1] > sample[n]:
  delta = sample[n+1] - sample[n]
else
  delta = 0xffffffff - sample[n] + sample[n+1]

In C you can use the following code:

int32_t delta_t = (int32_t)sample[n+1] - (int32_t)sample[n];

Binary data format

For certain SCPI commands, binary data is transmitted instead of ASCII text data. This approach reduces data traffic and accelerates data parsing. The device operates using Little Endian byte order. When executing the FETC:BIN? command, the response can either be a 4-byte IEEE compliant float or a 4-byte unsigned integer followed by a 4-byte IEEE compliant float, depending on the used bitmask parameter. The format closely resembles that of the FETC:ARR? command. The binary tuple list response for the FETC:ARR? command is interpreted as follows:

The initial 4-byte integer indicates the number of tuples in the list. Each tuple begins with a 4-byte integer representing a relative microsecond timestamp, followed by a 4-byte IEEE compliant float. There are no separators between the data or line endings to look for. First, use the read bytes command to determine the length of the tuple list. Then, calculate the payload length and read the tuple list afterward.

The following code gives an example to read and parse the binary tuple data in Python:

inst.write('FETC:ARR? 0,100')
vals = inst.read_bytes(4)
length = struct.unpack('<I', bytearray(vals[0 : 0 + 4]))[0]

vals = inst.read_bytes(8 * length)

res = []
for i in range(0, length, 8):
   reltime = struct.unpack('<I', bytearray(vals[i:i + 4]))[0]
   value   = struct.unpack('<f', bytearray(vals[i + 4:i + 8]))[0]
   res.append([reltime, value])

Scope Mode

The "Scope Mode" provides an oscilloscope-like measurement method in the PM100D2. It is exclusively available for the CW mode when using photodiode and thermopile sensors. A measurement is initiated by either an internal or external trigger, which directs data to a fixed-size internal buffer. For detailed pinning information of the external hardware trigger, please refer to the device manual. Once the buffer is completely filled, the measurement automatically stops. The data remains valid in the buffer until a new measurement is initiated. The PM100D2 always stores a total of 10,000 samples in its buffer. The maximum sample rate in scope mode is 100 kHz. With 10,000 samples, this results in a total measurement time of 100 ms at the highest resolution. For longer time intervals, averaging in scope mode must be employed. If averaging is set to two, the scope buffer fills at a rate of 50 kHz, resulting in a total time of 200 ms.

Before starting a scope measurement for e.g. optical power reading ensure:

  • Set manual range (Disables auto ranging of PM100D2 automatically), command: SENSe:POWer[:DC]:RANGe[:UPPer]
  • Set full bandwidth for Photodiode sensors (no analog filter), command: INPut[:PDIode]:FILTer[:LPASs][:STATe] 0
  • Choose CW mode for Photodiode sensors, command: SENSe:FREQuency:MODE CW
  • Disable acceleration for thermopile sensors, command: INPut:THERmopile:ACCelerator:AUTO 0
  • Set trigger threshold for internal hardware triggered signal, command: SENS:PEAK 30 (Not applicable for external triggering)

The scope mode is part of the MEAS SCPI command group. The basic command sequence looks like this:

  1. ABOR
    Abort any ongoing measurement
  2. CONF:ARR:CHA
    Configure unit for channel

  3. CONF:ARR 1
    Configure software Scope mode with averaging 1 OR
    CONF1:ARR:HWT 1,100
    Configure hardware Scope mode with averaging 1 and hpos 100 for internal trigger.

  4. INIT
    Starts a scope measurement
  5. FETC:STAT?
    Scope buffer filled? If not keep on asking. For timeout send ABOR finally
  6. FETC:STAT?
    Scope buffer filled? If not keep on asking. For timeout send ABOR finally
  7. ...
  8. FETC:STAT?
    Scope buffer filled returned true.
  9. FETC? 0
    Read scope buffer content at index 0
  10. FETC? 1
    Read scope buffer content at index 1
  11. ...
  12. FETC? 9999
    Read scope buffer content at index 9999

Once configured, a new scope measurement is taken with the following sequence:

  1. INIT
    Starts a scope measurement. Uses previous configuration. Invalidates previous buffer content!
  2. FETC:STAT?
    Scope buffer filled?
  3. ...
  4. FETC:STAT?
    Scope buffer filled returned true.
  5. FETC? 0
    Read scope buffer content at index 0
  6. FETC? 1
    Read scope buffer content at index 1
  7. ...
  8. FETC? 9999
    Read scope buffer content at index 9999

The scope mode supports two types of triggers. The first is the simpler software-triggered scope mode. In this mode, the sample buffer is filled immediately after receiving the INIT SCPI command. If FETC? is called before the buffer is filled, the command will block until the operation is complete. An averaging pre-scaler allows for sampling over longer periods with reduced resolution, and any incoming hardware triggers are ignored.
The second type is the more complex hardware-triggered scope mode. The following diagram illustrates this mode, with time flowing from left to right.

After receiving the first CONF:ARR:HWT the PM100D2 directly starts storing measurement results in the pre-trigger buffer. The CONF:ARR:HWT sets the averaging pre-scaler to allow longer time periods and the trigger horizontal position (hPos) to allow the scope to show also part of the signal before the trigger condition. The diagram shows an example for averaging = 1 and hPos = 100. The measurement is not yet started, and the trigger is not armed. Any incoming trigger condition is ignored.

With the INIT command the trigger becomes armed. The next trigger condition will start the scope measurement if the pre-trigger buffer is filled already. If not, the condition is skipped as well. When the trigger is valid the scope continues storing the measurement results in the post-trigger buffer and unarms the trigger automatically until a future INIT invalidates the previous buffer and starts a new measurement. Any incoming FETC? or FETC:ARR? during an ongoing measurement blocks until the buffer is filled completely. If the post-trigger buffer is filled completely, the PM100D2 continues measuring in the shadow pre-trigger buffer for the next measurement in background. The results of pre-trigger and post-trigger buffers stay valid and can be read with FETC? or FETC:ARR? at any time and speed.

The entire scope calculates in samples not time. The averaging allows to transfer samples to time at any time. The hPos is only allowed to be between 0 and 5000. The number of samples in post-trigger buffer always equals 10000 - hPos. The following example shows how to convert samples into time domain:

CONF1:ARR:HWT 5,150

  • Scope sample period time: Avg = 5 -> 100 kHz / 5 = 20 kHz = 50 us
  • Time before trigger condition: hPos = 150 Samples -> 150 * 50 us = 7,5 ms
  • Total time in buffer: 10000 * 50 us = 500 ms
  • Time after trigger condition = 500 ms – 7.5 ms or (10000 – 150) * 50 us = 492.5 ms

Notes:

  • A trigger condition can be forced by command TRIGer:ARRay:FORCe in hardware triggered Scope mode.
  • Scope mode is not available for Photodiode sensors in Peak mode.
  • Reading data in binary format by FETC:ARR? is much faster than the normal FETC? command.
  • The timebase is a relative wrapping uint32 microsecond counter. Read timebase section carefully.
  • There are more flags in the STAT:OPER:COND? register showing the state of the scope buffer.
  • For short scope measurements also the related convenience commands can be used: MEAS:ARR:HWT?, MEAS:ARR? or READ:ARR?

Burst Mode

The "Burst Mode" enables the storage of hardware-triggered measurement results in the device's internal buffer for later retrieval. It utilizes the same memory as the "Scope Mode." This mode is available exclusively for the CW mode when using photodiode and thermopile sensors. Multiple internal or external trigger conditions can initiate a measurement burst sequence if it has not already been started. The trigger repetition rate must be greater than or equal to 100 µs. For detailed pinning information of the external hardware trigger, please refer to the device manual. The device memory can store up to 15,000 samples. Each sequence is defined as follows:

  • Optional initial delay ("Init Delay") before starting measurement burst
  • Averaged burst measurement 1
  • Optional averaged burst measurement 2
  • Optional averaged burst measurement 3
  • ...

The optional initial delay allows you to postpone the burst sequence after the trigger condition in a 10 µs time grid. If this delay is not required, set it to 0 to start the sequence immediately. The sequence itself always contains at least one measurement but fewer than 5,000 averaged measurements. When the burst sequence stops, the next trigger will initiate an identical burst sequence. If there is no more free memory available in the device, any new data will be discarded. An optional averaging feature enables the burst sequence to measure longer time periods while maintaining the same number of stored samples. To store a single measurement result with the highest resolution for each trigger, use an initial delay of 0, set averaging to 1, and specify a burst length of 1.

Before starting a burst measurement for optical power reading ensure:

  • Set manual range (Disables auto ranging of PM100D2 automatically), command: SENSe:POWer[:DC]:RANGe[:UPPer]
  • Set full bandwidth for Photodiode sensors (no analog filter), command: INPut[:PDIode]:FILTer[:LPASs][:STATe] 0
  • Choose CW mode for Photodiode sensors, command: SENSe:FREQuency:MODE CW
  • Disable acceleration for thermopile sensors, command: INPut:THERmopile:ACCelerator:AUTO 0
  • Set trigger threshold for internal hardware triggered signal, command: SENS:PEAK 30 (Not applicable for external triggering)

The burst mode is part of the MEAS SCPI command group. The basic command sequence looks like this:

  1. ABOR
    Abort any ongoing measurement
  2. CONF:ARR:CHA
    Configure unit for channel 1
  3. CONF2:ARR:BUR 1,2,3
    Configure hardware GPIO triggered burst mode with initDelay = 1, BustCount = 2 and Averaging = 3.
  4. INIT
    Starts a burst measurement
  5. Trigger is active and burst sequences are stored in device buffer
  6. ABOR
    Stops burst measurement. Triggers are not longer observed
  7. FETC:ARR:LEN?
    Reads amount of samples in buffer
  8. FETC? 0
    Reads first sample of burst sequence
  9. FETC? 1
    Reads second sample of burst sequence
  10. ...

Once configured, a new burst measurement is taken with the following sequence:

  1. INIT
    Starts a burst measurement. Uses previous configuration
  2. Trigger is active and burst sequences are stored in device buffer
  3. ABOR
    Stops burst measurement. Triggers are not longer observed
  4. FETC:ARR:LEN?
    Reads amount of samples in buffer
  5. FETC? 0
    Reads first sample of burst sequence
  6. FETC? 1
    Reads second sample of burst sequence
  7. ...

The following diagram visualizes the mode in more detail. Time flows from left to right.

During the configuration of Burst Mode, all trigger conditions are ignored. After configuring the unit for the channel using commands such as CONF:ARR:CHAN, you can set up the Burst Mode in general. The CONF2:ARR:BUR command suffix selects the trigger input. By default, the frequency count threshold of channel 1 is used as the internal trigger condition. In most cases, it is advisable to use GPIO1 as the trigger input. The external 3.3V level trigger input responds to rising edges. The internal trigger of channel 1 activates when the signal exceeds the configured threshold (see command SENSe:PEAK). The CONF2:ARR:BUR parameters define the burst sequence to be stored after the trigger condition is met. If you call INIT afterwards, the trigger is armed, and a new burst measurement sequence begins. The burst results are stored without any separators in the burst memory. Each burst measurement point consists of a tuple containing the relative sample time and the value for channel 1. The example illustrates a burst configuration with an initial delay of 2 (20 µs), a burst count of 3, and an averaging setting of 2 (20 µs).

In the given example, the device will remain idle for 20 µs once the trigger is fired before it begins to store 3 samples in succession with an averaging of 20 µs. Any triggers that occur during this idle time will be postponed until the end of the burst. In such cases, the next burst will start immediately after the previous one. Ensure that the trigger repetition rate is greater than or equal to 100 µs (10 kHz). As long as there are rising edge trigger conditions and fewer than 15,000 samples are already stored, the burst sequence will be restarted. Once the measurement is complete, call ABOR to deactivate the burst mode. The previous results will remain valid until the next INIT command is issued. Use FETC:ARR:LEN? to determine the number of samples stored. You can then query the results using FETC? or the faster binary FETC:ARR? command multiple times. Calling any of these commands during an ongoing measurement will result in an error. However, you may call FETC:ARR:LEN? during the measurement to see how many results have already been stored.

The entire burst calculates in samples not time. The averaging allows to transfer samples to time at any time. The following example shows how to convert a parameter set of CONF2:ARR:BUR 5, 2, 3 into time domain:

  • Trigger source: 2 = GPIO or 1 = Channel 1
  • Init Delay time: InitDelay = 5, 10 us * 5 = 50 us
  • Averaging time: Averaging = 3, 10 us * 3 = 30 us
  • Burst sequence time: (InitDelay + SequcenceCount * Averaging) * 10 us = 110 us

Notes:

  • A trigger condition can be forced by command TRIGer:ARRay:FORCe in Burst mode.
  • Burst mode is not available for Photodiode sensors in Peak mode.
  • Reading data in binary format by FETC:ARR? is much faster than the normal FETC? command.
  • The timebase is a relative wrapping uint32 microsecond counter. Read timebase section carefully.

JSON Format

The Powermeter allows to export and import all measurement related parameters in JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) format. To simplify JSON transport via SCPI, the JSON response does not contain any line breaks or other formats characters. The JSON strings are not designed to change the measurement parameters. The intention is to provide a simple store and load parameters functionality. It is possible to change the sensors within the sensor type family. For example a photodiode might be replaced by another photodidode. Importing the photodiode parameters for a thermopile sensor will cause an error. If the sensor is changed during export and import it might be necessary to adapt some parameters to fit the new sensor. For exammple the wavelength needs to be adjusted. This adaption is optional on request. For the import the JSON string needs to be split into multiple SCPI command calls as the maximal request length is limited. The JSON parts are buffered in the device. Once the entire string has been transmitted the Powermeter will parse the JSON and update the parameters. To clear the device internal buffer in any case use the magic char #.

To export measurement parameters as a single line JSON string use SYSTem:PARAmeter:EXPOrt:JSON?. The following example response has been manually formated to show the content.


    
    
To import JSON parameters the large JSON string needs to be split into multiple frames as the maximal SCPI request 
      length is limited to 200 characters. Use the magic char # to discard any previous content of the device internal 
      JSON input buffer. The Powermeter counts the curly brackets to decide when the entire JSON string has been written.
      It is best practice to check for errors after import to see if operation was successful. Use SYST:ERR? to query error queue.
      The following example shows how to import parameters in multiple SCPI command calls. To keep this demo simple the request
      length is even shorter than the allowed 200 characters what is also valid but less efficent. 
    

    
    
      
  1. SYST:PARA:IMPO:JSON 1,'randomContent'
    Generate some invalid JSON to show clear feature. Don't do this.
    2. 
      
  2. SYST:PARA:IMPO:JSON 1,'#{“pm“:{“name“:“PM100D2“,“ser“:“P00000001“,“calD“:'
    Use magic char to clear nonsense and start writing JSON
    3. 
      
  3. SYST:PARA:IMPO:JSON 1,'“04-Feb-2025“,“adap“:1},“ntc“:{“r0“:10000.00,“b“:3988.00}'
    Continue writing next JSON part
    4.     
      
  4. ...
    5. 
    

    
Details and Limitations

    
    
      
  1. It is allowed to import parameters of another Powermeter with the same name. Is is not possible to import JSON parameters of another Powermeter even within the PM100Dx family.
    2. 
      
  2. If no sensor is currently connected, no sensor parameters are imported. The sensor parameter json part will be ignored.
    3. 
      
  3. As JSON does not define infinity or nan (Not a Number) as valid reals, these values are retruned as string.
    4. 
    

    
The following code gives an example to export and later inport the parameters using Python:

    

      #export the data

      importData = d.query(“SYST:PARA:EXPO:JSON?“)

      

      #Clear any pending data in buffer

      d.write(“SYST:PARA:IMPO:JSON 1, '#'“)

      #Program JSON string chucks

      for i in range(0, len(importData), 200):

        d.write(f“SYST:PARA:IMPO:JSON 1, '{importData[i : i + 200]}'“)

      

      #check for import error

      print(d.auto_query(“SYST:ERR?“))

    

    
Analog Output

    
The PM100D2 is equipped with an analog output featuring an SMA connector that
    delivers light sensor-related analog unipolar voltages from 0 V to 2.4 V. This analog
    output has a 100 Ohm output impedance. 
     This section describes the different analog output
    strategies available. To switch between the output strategies, use the SCPI command
    SOUR:VOLT:ROUT.

    
    
Pure Analog Output

    
The pure analog output mode is the default setting. In this mode, the amplified
    light sensor current or voltage is directly output after the selected range amplifier.
    The output voltage is not wavelength or zero corrected. The bandwidth is determined by
    the selected measurement range, and switching measurement ranges results in a stepwise
    change in the output voltage. The following image illustrates the pure analog output
    for a triangle input signal and auto-ranging enabled to demonstrate its behavior.

    
    

    
    
Generated Power or Energy

    
The generated power or energy output is produced by an internal 12-bit DAC
    operating at a rate of 1 kSPS. This signal is both wavelength and zero corrected. You
    can use the SCPI command SOUR:VOLT:CORR:SLOP to adjust
    the resolution by modifying the slope. During ranging pauses, the Powermeter employs
    linear interpolation to maintain the signals. For sporadic pulsed input from
    photodiodes or pyro signals, the analog output update rate is dependent on the signal
    frequency but is capped at 1 kHz. In this case, linear interpolation is not applied
    between samples, resulting in step functions. To smooth the output signal, the
    generated power or energy mode utilizes a low pass filter with a cutoff frequency of
    10 kHz. The following image demonstrates the generated power or energy output and
    auto-ranging enabled for a triangle input signal.

    
    

    
    
Generated Power in dBm

    
The logarithmic power output in dBm is generated by an internal 12-bit DAC at a
    rate of 1 kSPS. This signal is wavelength and zero corrected. You can use the SCPI
    commands SOUR:VOLT:LOG:VOLT:MAX and SOUR:VOLT:LOG:DYRA to configure the output voltage range.
    During ranging pauses, the Powermeter uses linear interpolation to maintain the
    signals. Note that this mode is not available for photodiodes in peak measurement
    mode. To smooth the output signal, the generated power or energy mode employs a low
    pass filter with a cutoff frequency of 10 kHz. The following image illustrates the
    generated power or energy output and auto-ranging enabled for a triangle input
    signal.

    
    

    
    
Function Generator

    
The analog output can be configured to produce square, sawtooth, triangle, or
    sinusoidal voltages. Custom-defined signals are also possible. The 12-bit DAC utilizes
    a 128-entry lookup table to output the signal with a maximum update rate of 1 MSPS.
    Use the SCPI command SOUR:VOLT:GEN:ENAB to configure and
    control the function generator. To smooth the generated output signals, two different
    optional low pass filters are available, with cutoff frequencies of 10 kHz or 100
    kHz.

    
    
Customer Signal

    
The analog output voltage is generated by the 12-bit DAC using the SCPI command
    SOUR:VOLT. To smooth the output signal, the customer
    signal employs a low pass filter with a cutoff frequency of 10 kHz.


    

    
Customer Calibration

    
To allow customers to perform in-house corrections for their sensors at a limited number of wavelengths, the PM100D2 
      includes support for customer calibration. The device can store up to four distinct customer calibration data sets, enabling 
      configurations such as four sensors each with a single correction curve or two sensors each with dual correction curves. 
      Each data set supports corrections at up to 10 wavelength set points, with linear interpolation applied between these points. 
      The correction is limited to a factor between 0.8 and 1.2 to prevent unrealistic calibration values.
      These customer calibration objects are stored persistently in the device's memory and do not interfere with the factory 
      calibration of the sensor or power meter. The calibration is linked to the sensor head via its serial number. The 
      measurement module combines the sensor's responsivity curve with the customer correction factors, as illustrated 
      in the following image: 
    

    
    
The sensor EEPROM stores Res(λ). The customer calibration results in a factor Cus(λ). So the firmware effective responsivity 
    gets calculated: Res(λ) * Cus(λ). Even if there is a valid customer calibration for a sensor it might be disabled and is not used. 
    Changing or enabling/disabling a customer calibration always requires the sensor to get reconnected. This can be done weather 
    physically or with the SCPI command SENS1:REI.
    


    
The factor can be determined with a comparison measurement with a known wavelength and power level. Best practice is to 
      average some measurements, performed with the commands SENS:AVER 300 and 
      MEAS?. The factor can then be calculated with the formula Cus(λ) = AVG Meas Power / Reference Power.


    
The following SCPI command sequence shows how to write a customer calibration:

    SENS1:CORR:CSET:PRE "191113108","2019-11-28","TestUser",1

    SENS1:CORR:CSET:POIN 400,1.1,450,1.1,500,1.1,550,1.1

    SENS1:CORR:CSET1:DEF

    SENS1:CORR:CSET1:STAT 1

    SENS1:REI
    


    
To delete a customer calibration use this sequence:
    SENS1:CORR:CSET1:PRE "","","",1

    SENS1:CORR:CSET1:DEF

    SENS1:CORR:CSET1:STAT 0

    SENS1:REI
    


    
The customer calibration wizard is available as part of the OPM.


    
SCPI Registers

    
The SCPI system defines a status reporting system based on status register sets. Every state or event is mapped to a single bit in the values of the register sets. 
    The PM100D2 defines the following register sets: 

    
    
      
  • AUXilary: Auxiliary system monitoring like shutter or fan.
    • 
      
  • OPERation: Measurement state monitoring.
    • 
      
  • QUESTionalbe: Measurement result reliability status monitoring.
    • 
      
  • STDandard Byte: SCPI global system status byte.
    • 
    


    
Every register set contains 5 registers.

    
    
      
  • CONDition: The Condition register monitors the actual state. For example if a sensor is currently connected or not.
    • 
      
  • PTRansition: The Positive Transition register masks bit changes from 0 to 1 of the Condition register to the Event register.
    • 
      
  • NTRansition: The Negative Transition register masks bit changes from 1 to 0 of the Condition register to the Event register.
    • 
      
  • EVENT: The Event register shows changes of the Condition register. Some conditions only last for a short moment and are otherwise hard to detect.
    • 
      
  • ENABle: The Enable register masks if changes of the Event registers are forwarded to a higher level hierarchy Condition register.
    • 
    

    
The following image visualizes the logical relation between the registers.

      
      
The Condition register always reflects the current state. For example if a sensor is connected or not. The Positive Transition register masks if a
      certain condition becomes true (bit changes from 0 to 1) to set the bit at the same position in the Event register. For example to set the Event register 
      bit to 1 if the sensor got connected. 
The Negative Transition register tests if condition becomes false to update the Event register. For example to 
      set event register bit to 1 if the sensor got disconnected. The Enable register masks if changes of the Event register should be reported to the 
      higher level hierarchy Condition register. The register sets are logically chained. The following section will provide further details about the chaining.

      
All registers except the STB register group are 16 bit wide. The following paragraph gives a short description of bit mask in general. Bit mask use the binary
      representation of numbers to store boolean states (true, false) or (active, inactive). This is a memory saving way to store multiple conditions at once.
      If you look on a decimal number 9 for example the binary representation is 1001 = 1 * 2 ^ 4 + 1 * 2 ^ 0. This bit mask means condition at bit position 1 and 4 are true. 
      All other conditions are false as all other bits are set to 0.

      To test if a certain bit is set to 1 you can either use bit logic operations or use generic mathematic operations. Bit logic operations are available in almost every 
      programming language. In Python you would write something like condition = bitmask & (1 << position).

      If you want to use standard math you can use the following formula:
      

      

      
The register sets are linked together in an hirarchical way. This enables you to check for a summarized condition only. If the 
      highlevel condition becomes true you can than go down the hierarchy to query the details causing the event.

      
      
      
The STAT:OPER status register set contains state information about the instrument's normal
      operation. The register set might report to the SCPI Standard Byte register bit 7 if 
      STAT:OPER:ENAB bit mask is set active.


     
     
The QUEStionable status register set contains bits which give an indication of the quality of
      various aspects of the measurement signal. The register set might report to the SCPI Standard 
      Byte register bit 3 if STAT:OPER:ENAB bit mask is set active.

     
      
    
The AUXilary register set contains state informatin about the instrument auxiliary like the 
    NTC or power supply. The register set might report to the SCPI Standard 
    Byte register bit 0 if STAT:OPER:ENAB bit mask is set active.

        INP#:THER:ACC:AUTOEnables/Disables thermopile prediction

      

      

        
INPut
#
:THERmopile:ACCelerator:AUTO 
<enable>

        
Suffixe
    
          
  • Sufix 1uint light sensor frontend channel. Default is 1.
    • 
        


        
Parameters
    
              
  • enablebool true to enable thermopile prediction. False to disable.
    • 
        


        
Use this command to enable or disable the thermopile sensor value prediction algorithm. Thermopile sensors can respond slowly to rapid changes in light intensity. The prediction algorithm automatically calculates the resulting power, following a logarithmic function during positive jumps and a 1/e function during negative jumps. The sensor behaves like a capacitor, and in both scenarios, the signal reaches 99% of its final level after a time period of 5 Tau, at which point the prediction is automatically halted. Tau is a sensor-specific constant stored in the head's EEPROM. For adapter sensors, Tau can be modified using the INP#:THER:ACC:TAU function.         FETC:ARR?Returns one ore more binary encoded measurement results

      

      

        
FETCh:ARRay[:BINAry]? 
<offset>
, 
<length>
, 
<bitmask>

        
Parameters
    
              
  • offsetuint start reading array measurements at this offset. Only valid for scope and burst mode.
    • 
              
  • lengthuint amount of measurements to read at once. Max is 100.
    • 
           
  • bitmaskuint Optional! Use bit 0 to query binary without timestemp. And 1 to query with timestamps (default).
    • 
        


        
Response
    
          
  • countbinary amount of binary results as 4 byte unsigned integer.
    • 
          
  • databinary list of binary results. Four bytes relative uint time between samples. Four bytes IEEE float.
    • 
        


        
Binary array fetch is a component of the SCPI measurement system, which includes commands such as ABOR#, CONF#, INIT#, and FETC:ARR?. This command retrieves one or multiple measurement results in a binary format. The unit of measurement is determined by the previously configured unit (e.g., CONF#) and the used masurement mode like e.g. scope mode. If there are no pending measurement results, the command directly returns with 0 length result.
 You can also fetch one more multiple results in text format using the FETC:ARR:TEXT? command. To fetch single results only, use the FETC#? or FETC#:BINA? commands.
 For light sensors, the command return one ore multiple measurement results of the device internal queue starting with the oldest element. If there are no elements in the queue the command will respond with a 4 bytes length list set to 0. Be aware that the device's internal measurement result queue has a limited capacity. You can check the fill level and maximum queue length by calling FETC:ARR:LEN?. The queue stores measurement results along with their timestamps, and you can fetch the results with or without timestamps. For further details about the parameters, please continue reading. The stored measurements can be absolute or relative, depending on the delta mode offset (e.g., SENS#:POW:REF) and its enabled state (e.g., SENS#:POW:REF:STAT). By default, delta mode is disabled.
  The maximum measurement and query frequency is 1 kHz (with averaging set to 1). All measurement results within a 1-millisecond period are averaged. To change the averaging settings, call SENS#:AVER. Averaging is applicable only for photodiodes in continuous wave (CW) mode, while peak, temperature, resistance, and pulse width measurements are taken independently of averaging.
 Exercise caution when measuring pyro sensors or photodiodes in peak mode. It is advisable to call FETC#:STAT? or check the DataReadyToFetch flag in the Operation Status register STAT#:OPER:COND? before invoking FETC:ARR?. Additionally, you can query the Questionable Status register STAT:QUES:COND? to verify if the measurement results are valid and not infinite. Use FETC:ARR:LEN? to determine how many results are ready to be fetched.
 When measuring 4-quadrant voltages, the result will contain quadrupel for every measurment representing the four quadrants. For beam position measurements, the result will include two floats representing the x and y coordinates. If timestamps are enabled, an additional 4 bytes unsigned integer value will be included in the heading of every quadrupel (4Q voltages) or tuple (Position).
 This SCPI command can also be used to fetch results from scope or burst mode measurements, where the offset and bitmask parameters are useful. It is advisable to query these results with timestamps. Before quering the results of burst mode, ensure to abort the ongoing measurement using ABOR# command. Refer to the Scope section for more information.
 The optional offset parameter is relevant only for scope or burst measurement results, indicating the position of the element to fetch from the device's internal buffer. For all other modes, this parameter is ignored.
 The optional bitmask parameter has the following significance: 
     
  • bit 0: Set to 1 when querying with timestamps; set to 0 for values only.
    •  
  • bit 1-31: Reserved
    •  
 The timestamp in the response is a relative 32-bit unsigned microsecond counter used to calculate the delta time between two measurements. It does not represent wall time and will overflow after approximately 71 minutes.  The little-endian binary format consists of the following elements: 

        
>> FETC:ARR? 0,100
<< <4 Bytes length all 0> (No data available)
>> FETC:ARR? 0,100
<< <4 Bytes length><length * (4 bytes relative time uint + 4 Bytes float for power)> (Power sensor measurement example with timestamp)

        FETC#?Fetches a single measurement result from the device as text

Fetch is a component of the SCPI measurement system, which includes commands such as ABOR#, CONF#, INIT#, and FETC#?. This command retrieves the oldest measurement result from the device's internal fixed-size queue and returns the result as text. The unit of measurement is determined by the previously configured unit (e.g., CONF#). Measurements can be absolute or relative, depending on the delta mode offset (e.g., SENS#:POW:REF) and its enabled state (e.g., SENS#:POW:REF:STAT). By default, delta mode is disabled.
  If there are no pending measurement results, the command will block until the previously initiated measurement is complete, at which point it will return the result. During this waiting period, the remote interface will be blocked and unable to process any further SCPI commands. You can specify an optional timeout parameter to limit the waiting time. For more details, please continue reading.
  If measurement results are already available in the queue, the command will return the oldest result immediately. However, be aware that the device's internal measurement result queue has a limited capacity. You can check the fill level and maximum queue length by calling FETC:ARR:LEN?. The queue stores measurement results along with their timestamps, and you can fetch the results with or without timestamps. For further details, please continue reading.
  The maximum measurement and query frequency is 1 kHz (with averaging set to 1). All measurement results within a 1-millisecond period are averaged. To change the averaging settings, call SENS#:AVER. Averaging is applicable only for photodiodes in continuous wave (CW) mode, while peak, temperature, resistance, and pulse width measurements are taken independently of averaging.
 Exercise caution when measuring pyro sensors or photodiodes in peak mode. If the input signal does not consistently generate pulses (e.g., during single pulse measurements or at low repetition rates), the command may block for several seconds and could time out after 10 seconds without a pulse. For modulated signals, it is advisable to call FETC#:STAT? or check the DataReadyToFetch flag in the Operation Status register STAT#:OPER:COND? before invoking FETC#?. Additionally, you can query the Questionable Status register STAT:QUES:COND? to verify if the measurement results are valid and not infinite. Use FETC:ARR:LEN? to determine how many results are ready to be fetched.
 When measuring 4-quadrant voltages, the result will consist of four floats representing the four quadrants. For beam position measurements, the result will include two floats representing the x and y coordinates. If timestamps are enabled, an additional uint32 value will be included in the heading.
 This SCPI command can also be used to fetch results from scope or burst mode measurements, where the offset and bitmask parameters are useful. It is advisable to query these results with timestamps.
 You can also fetch the results in binary format using the FETC#:BINA? command. To fetch multiple results at once, use the FETC:ARR:TEXT? or FETC:ARR? commands.
 The optional offset parameter is relevant only for scope or burst measurement results, indicating the position of the element to fetch from the device's internal buffer. For all other modes, this parameter is ignored.
 The optional timeout parameter specifies the maximum time to wait for a measurement result in milliseconds. If the value is less than 5000 milliseconds, the function will return 0 or 0,0 if queried with timestamps. If the value exceeds 5000 milliseconds, the function will enqueue a SCPI error to the error queue, and no response will be written. Use SYST:ERR? to read the error queue. By default, the timeout value is set to 10000 milliseconds.
 The optional bitmask parameter has the following significance: 
     
  • bit 0: Set to 1 when querying with timestamps; set to 0 for values only.
    •  
  • bit 1-31: Reserved
    •  
 The timestamp is a relative 32-bit unsigned microsecond counter used to calculate the delta time between two measurements. It does not represent wall time and will overflow after approximately 71 minutes. For details on calculating delta time, please refer to the Slow measurement section. For more detailed information about the measurement mode in general, please refer also to the Slow measurement section.

Use this command to initiate a new single measurement for a unit that has been previously configured. The INIT# command is part of the SCPI measurement system, which includes ABOR#, CONF#, INIT#, and FETC#?. This command requires that at least one of the configuration commands has been executed beforehand. When the Powermeter receives the INIT# command, it will synchronize with any ongoing measurement and begin a new conversion. The measurement results will be stored in the device's internal queue, but please note that the length of the result queue is limited. You can use the FETC:ARR:LEN? command to check the maximum queue length. The maximum measurement frequency is 1 kHz (with averaging set to 1), and all measurement results within a 1-millisecond period will be averaged. To adjust the averaging, call SENS#:AVER. Averaging is applicable only for photodiodes in CW mode, while all peak, temperature, resistance, and pulse width measurements are taken independently of averaging with different update  rates.
 Use FETC#? to wait until at least one measurement has been completed and to retrieve the result. Alternatively, you can use the non-blocking FETC:ARR:TEXT? command to read multiple results from the queue simultaneously. For faster data exchange, consider using the FETC:ARR? or FETC:ARR? commands.
 You can also use the INIT#:CONT command to start a new continuous measurement sequence.

        
>> INIT

Use this command to initiate a new continuous measurement for a previously configured unit. This command is part of the SCPI measurement system, which includes ABOR#, CONF#, INIT#:CONT, and FETC#?. It is essential that at least one of the configuration commands has been executed prior to this command. When the Powermeter receives the INIT#:CONT command, it will commence a continuous measurement sequence with the configured averaging settings. The measurement results will be stored in the device's internal queue. Please note that the length of this internal queue is limited; you can use the FETC:ARR:LEN? command to check the maximum queue length. To terminate the measurement sequence, use the ABOR# command. 
  The maximum measurement frequency is 1 kHz (with averaging set to 1), and all measurement results within a 1-millisecond interval will be averaged. To modify the averaging settings, call SENS#:AVER. Averaging is applicable only for photodiodes in continuous wave (CW) mode, while peak, temperature, and resistance measurements are taken independently of averaging and have different update rates.
  Once continuous measurement has started, use FETC#? to wait for a new measurement to be taken and to retrieve the result. Additionally, you can utilize the non-blocking FETC:ARR:TEXT? command to retrieve one or multiple results. For faster data exchange, consider using the FETC:ARR? or FETC:ARR? commands.
  Continuous measurements are not available for scope or burst measurements, nor for pulse width or duty cycle measurements. You can also use the INIT# command to initiate a new single measurement.

        MEAS#?Measures the sensor averaged power in Watt or dBm

      

      

        
MEASure
#
[:SCALar][:POWer]?

        
Suffixe
    
          
  • Sufix 1uint channel the sensor head is connected to. Here always 1 (default)
    • 
        


        
Response
    
          
  • powerfloat power in Watt or dBm. May be INFINITY or -INFINITY if signal is out of measurement range
    • 
        


        
Use this command to measure the average power in Watts for Photodiode, Thermopile, or 4-Quadrant Thermopile sensors. When the Powermeter receives a MEAS#? command, it will start a new measurement and return the result once enough data has been averaged. The maximum frequency for command calls is 1 kHz (with averaging set to 1), and all measurement results within a 1-millisecond window are averaged.
 During the measurement, the remote interface will be blocked for up to 10 seconds while waiting for a measurement result. During this time, the remote interface will not be able to process any additional SCPI requests. The result of this command may be either absolute or relative, depending on the delta mode offset and its enabled state. For more information, refer to the SENS#:POW:REF and SENS#:POW:REF:STAT commands. By default, delta mode is disabled. You can also check the Questionable Status register STAT:QUES:COND? to confirm the validity of the measurement results and ensure they are not infinite.
 In CW measurement mode, the averaging process can be adjusted using the SENS#:AVER command. You can either set the range manually using SENS#:POW:RANG or enable auto-ranging with SENS#:POW:RANG:AUTO.
 For Photodiode in peak mode, averaging is not applied in this sensor measurement mode. The Powermeter utilizes an internal threshold for peak detection. You can manually set the threshold level using SENS#:PEAK or enable auto-ranging with SENS#:POW:RANG:AUTO for repetitive pulsed input signals with a repetition rate greater than 5 Hz. For such repetitive input signals, you can also use the peak-finder background operation to automatically set the range and threshold parameters once. The peak-finder is a one-time auto-ranging operation.
 For non-repetitive pulse signals (such as single pulse measurements or low repetition rates), you will need to manually select the range and threshold. In these cases, it is advisable not to invoke this command. Instead, consider using INIT# to initiate a new measurement, followed by FETC#:STAT? or checking the DataReadyToFetch flag in the Operation Status register STAT#:OPER:COND? before finally calling FETC#?.
 For further details about this measurement mode, please refer to the Slow Measurement section.

        
>> MEAS?
<< 3.34e-5

        
Photodiode Thermopile and 4-Quadrant Thermopile only. Be careful when measuring single pulse events. Read details carefully.

        MEAS#:FREQ?Measures the modulated sensor signal frequency in Hz

      

      

        
MEASure
#
[:SCALar]:FREQuency?

        
Suffixe
    
          
  • Sufix 1uint channel the sensor head is connected to. Here always 1 (default)
    • 
        


        
Response
    
          
  • frequfloat frequency in Hz. Might be 0 Hz for CW signals
    • 
        


        
Use this command to measure the modulation frequency of the input signal in Hz. The Powermeter updates the frequency reading at intervals of 2 Hz or less, depending on the input frequency. For frequency measurement, the input signal is compared to a threshold level, which can be set using the SENS#:PEAK command. If the input signal exceeds the threshold, it is detected as high; otherwise, the Powermeter identifies it as low.
 The accuracy of the frequency measurement depends on the input signal frequency. The Powermeter employs edge counting for input signals above approximately 500 Hz and uses period measurement for slower signal frequencies. Edge counting always yields a whole number frequency. If a continuous wave (CW) signal is input, the frequency will be reported as 0. Note that averaging via SENS#:AVER is not applicable for frequency measurements.
 For photodiodes, ensure that you select the high bandwidth limit using INP#:FILT for accurate frequency measurements.

[:SCALar]:PDENsity?

        
Suffixe
    
          
  • Sufix 1uint channel the sensor head is connected to. Here always 1 (default)

    • 
        


        
Use this command to measure the average power density in Watt per square cm for Photodiode, Thermopile, or 4-Quadrant Thermopile sensors. When the Powermeter receives a MEAS#:PDEN? command, it will start a new measurement and return the result once enough data has been averaged. The maximum frequency for command calls is 1 kHz (with averaging set to 1), and all measurement results within a 1-millisecond window are averaged. To change the density reference beam size, use the SENS#:CORR:BEAM command.
 During the measurement, the remote interface will be blocked for up to 10 seconds while waiting for a measurement result. During this time, the remote interface will not be able to process any additional SCPI requests. The result of this command may be either absolute or relative, depending on the delta mode offset and its enabled state. For more information, refer to the SENS#:POW:REF and SENS#:POW:REF:STAT commands. By default, delta mode is disabled. You can also check the Questionable Status register STAT:QUES:COND? to confirm the validity of the measurement results and ensure they are not infinite.
 In CW measurement mode, the averaging process can be adjusted using the SENS#:AVER command. You can either set the range manually using SENS#:POW:RANG or enable auto-ranging with SENS#:POW:RANG:AUTO.
 For Photodiode in peak mode, averaging is not applied in this sensor measurement mode. The Powermeter utilizes an internal threshold for peak detection. You can manually set the threshold level using SENS#:PEAK or enable auto-ranging with SENS#:POW:RANG:AUTO for repetitive pulsed input signals with a repetition rate greater than 5 Hz. For such repetitive input signals, you can also use the peak-finder background operation to automatically set the range and threshold parameters once. The peak-finder is a one-time auto-ranging operation.
 For non-repetitive pulse signals (such as single pulse measurements or low repetition rates), you will need to manually select the range and threshold. In these cases, it is advisable not to invoke this command. Instead, consider using INIT# to initiate a new measurement, followed by FETC#:STAT? or checking the DataReadyToFetch flag in the Operation Status register STAT#:OPER:COND? before finally calling FETC#?.
 For further details about this measurement mode, please refer to the Slow Measurement section.

        READ:ARR?Restarts a previously configured scope capture

      

      

        
READ:ARRay?

        
Response
    
          
  • countbinary Amount of binary tuples in result as four bytes uint.
    • 
          
  • databinary A list of binary tuples, each containing four bytes of relative uint time and four bytes of IEEE float.
    • 
        


        
Use this command to restart a previously configured scope capture. It utilizes the previous scope configuration and initializes a new hardware or software-triggered measurement sequence. The command will block until the measurement is finished. It will return the first 100 samples as binary tuples. To query the remaining samples, call FETC:ARR? multiple times afterwards. Please refer to FETC:ARR? for a description of the binary data format.             This SCPI command serves as a convenience function that includes the SCPI command sequence: ABOR#, INIT#, and finally FETC:ARR?. Please note that this command is implemented for convenience and should not be used for single pulse measurements. The internal FETC:ARR? call will wait for the trigger to fire and for the internal scope buffer to be completely filled before returning. It is very likely that a timeout error will occur. In the case of a timeout error, please wait more than 10 seconds before sending the next SCPI command. Otherwise, the remote interface connection may crash. Please be aware that the entire remote interface blocks while waiting for the measurement, so sending ABOR# or calling TRIG:ARR:FORC will not work.
 For single pulses or sporadic signals, it is better to use individual SCPI commands and call FETC#:STAT? or check for the DataReadyToFetch flag in the Operation Status register STAT#:OPER:COND? before finally calling FETC:ARR?.
 

        
>> READ:ARR?
<< <4 Bytes length>

        
Depending on signal this command may take several seconds to complete. For sporadic single pulse signals read MEAS#:ARR:HWT? carefully.

        
The command finally return first 100 tuples. Call FETC:ARR? to get all data afterwards.

        SENS#:CORR:COLL:ZEROStarts a zeroing of the sensor

      

      

        
SENSe
#
:CORRection:COLLect:ZERO[:INITiate]

        
Suffixe
    
          
  • Sufix 1uint channel the sensor head is connected to. Here always 1 (default).
    • 
        


        
Use this command to initiate a dark current or voltage correction for the sensor. Before starting the correction, ensure that the light source is not illuminating the sensor area and that the sensor is completely covered. This command only begins the zeroing procedure, which runs in the background. During the zeroing process, measurements cannot be taken. To check if the zeroing is still in progress, use SENS#:CORR:COLL:ZERO:STAT? or poll the Zeroing flag in STAT#:OPER:COND?. If the sensor is not fully covered, the zeroing procedure may automatically time out with an error code. To abort a previously started procedure, use the SENS#:CORR:COLL:ZERO:ABOR command. Once zeroing is complete (whether due to error or success), you may want to check for any errors using the SYST:ERR? command. For relative measurements in relation to ambient light, utilize delta mode commands such as SENS#:POW:REF, as the maximum zero correction parameter is limited to a small current. If you wish to set a custom zero value, use the SENS#:CORR:COLL:ZERO:MAGN command. You can also check the zeroing flag bit 7 in the Operation Status register with STAT#:OPER:COND? to determine if zeroing is ongoing.

        
>> SENS:CORR:COLL:ZERO

        
Do not use zeroing to make relative measurements compared to ambient light. Zeroing is only available for Photodiode in CW mode.

        
Best practice is to cover the entire sensor aperture during zero procedure.

Typically, you should allow the Powermeter to determine the zero value itself by using the SENS#:CORR:COLL:ZERO command. For relative measurements in relation to ambient light, utilize delta mode commands such as SENS#:POW:REF, as the maximum zero correction is limited and exceeding this limit will result in an error. Please note that the zero parameter is not stored persistently and will be lost after a reboot!

        
>> SENS:CORR:COLL:ZERO:MAGN 0

        
Zero parameter is accessible for Photodiode in CW mode and Thermopile and 4-Qudadrant Thermopile.

        
Set to 0 to disable zero correction.

TLPMX_getCurrentRange(), TLPMX_getCurrentRanges()

      

    

    

      

        SENS#:CURR:RANG:AUTOSets current measurement auto-ranging

      

      

        
SENSe
#
:CURRent[:DC]:RANGe:AUTO 
<state>

        
Suffixe
    
          
  • Sufix 1uint channel the sensor head is connected to. Here always 1 (default).
    • 
        


        
Parameters
    
              
  • statebool 1 to enable auto-ranging, 0 otherwise.
    • 
        


        
This command enables or disables the auto-ranging feature for current measurement. When auto-ranging is active, the Powermeter compares the measured signal to the currently used measurement range. If the signal falls outside the optimal range, the Powermeter automatically adjusts the measurement range. Changing the measurement range will temporarily interrupt the measurement for up to 10 milliseconds to allow the analog hardware to stabilize. After this period, measurement will automatically resume.
 For continuous wave (CW) signals, the current auto-ranging feature automatically selects the optimal range for measuring your signal effectively. You can use the SENS#:CURR:RANG? function to check the currently selected measurement range. When measuring modulated signals in CW mode, it is advisable to manually set the range using SENS#:CURR:RANG to avoid the meter from permanently switching ranges.
 When using auto-ranging in peak mode, the input signal must consist of repetitive pulses with a pulse-to-pulse voltage difference of less than 5 percent. In this mode, the Powermeter automatically selects the appropriate range and adjusts the threshold for peak detection. If the signal is lost, the algorithm will initiate a peak-finding procedure after a timeout of 500 ms. For all other types of pulse signals, you will need to manually set the range using SENS#:CURR:RANG? and adjust the threshold with SENS#:PEAK.
  The state of auto-ranging is stored persistently and will be restored after a reboot. If you change the sensor type, auto-ranging is enabled by default. You can check the ranging status by looking for flag bit 2 in the Operation Status register using the STAT#:OPER:COND? command to determine if the ranging pause is currenly active.

        
>> SENS:CURR:RANG:AUTO 1

        
For scope mode it makes sense to disable auto-ranging to get a seamless result stream.

TLPMX_getEnergyRange()

      

    

    

      

        SENS#:ENER:RANG:AUTOSets energy measurement auto-ranging

      

      

        
SENSe
#
:ENERgy:RANGe:AUTO 
<state>

        
Suffixe
    
          
  • Sufix 1uint channel the sensor head is connected to. Here always 1 (default).
    • 
        


        
Parameters
    
              
  • statebool 1 to enable auto-ranging, 0 otherwise.
    • 
        


        
This command enables or disables the auto-ranging feature for energy measurement. When auto-ranging is active, the Powermeter compares the measured peak values to the currently used measurement range. If the signal falls outside the optimal range, the Powermeter automatically adjusts the measurement range. Additionally, the meter modifies the peak detection threshold when auto-ranging is enabled. Changing the measurement range will temporarily interrupt the measurement for up to 10 milliseconds to allow the analog hardware to stabilize. After this period, measurement will automatically resume.
 Auto-ranging for energy measurement requires a repetitive pulsed input signal with a repetition rate greater than 5 Hz. It also relies on small changes (<5%) between the pulses. If auto-ranging loses peaks due to an incorrect threshold, it will automatically initiate the peak finder algorithm after a timeout of 500 milliseconds.
 You can inquire about the current range using the SENS#:ENER:RANG? command. If you set a manual range using the SENS#:ENER:RANG command, auto-ranging will be disabled automatically. The state of auto-ranging is stored persistently and will be restored after a reboot. If you change the sensor type, auto-ranging is enabled by default. You can check the ranging status by looking for flag bit 2 in the Operation Status register using the STAT#:OPER:COND? command to determine if the ranging process was completed successfully.

        
>> SENS:ENER:RANG:AUTO 1

    • 
        


        
Use this command to set the peak detection threshold as a percentage. This percentage is relative to the maximum value of the currently used measurement range. For modulated photodiode signals, the Powermeter compares the sensor signal to the threshold to determine if a new pulse has been detected.         SENS#:PEAK:SEARStarts or aborts the peak-finder background operation

      

      

        
SENSe
#
:PEAKdetector:SEARch

        
Suffixe
    
          
  • Sufix 1uint channel the sensor head is connected to. Here always 1 (default).
    • 
        


        
Use this command to initiate or abort the peak-finder background algorithm. When the Powermeter receives this command, it will halt normal measurements and attempt to asynchronously determine the optimal measurement range and peak-detection threshold for the pulsed input signal. Please note that auto-ranging will be disabled once the peak-finder algorithm is started.
 You can call SENS#:PEAK:SEAR? or check bit 3 of the one-time auto-ranging flag  in the Operation Status register with STAT#:OPER:COND? to determine if the  auto-ranging algorithm is currently running in the background. The peak-finder algorithm will always terminate, even if no pulses are detected. This algorithm is specifically designed for repetitive pulsed input signals measured with photodiodes in peak mode or pyro sensors. To switch the photodiode to peak mode, use the SENS#:FREQ:MODE command.
 If you wish to abort a previously initiated procedure, simply send the same command while the peak-finder is active. If the peak-finder completes (whether successfully or due to an error), you may want to check for any errors using the SYST:ERR? command. You can also use SENS#:PEAK? and, for example, SENS#:POW:RANG? to retrieve the automatically set parameters later. .     

        
>> SENS:PEAK:SEAR

        
Only available for repetitive pulsed input signals in peak mode measured by Photodiode or Pyro sensors.

        
For CW mode you can use SENS#:POW:RANG:SEAR to find a manual range fitting your input signal best.

        SENS#:POW:RANG:AUTOSets power measurement auto-ranging

      

      

        
SENSe
#
:POWer[:DC]:RANGe:AUTO 
<state>

        
Suffixe
    
          
  • Sufix 1uint channel the sensor head is connected to. Here always 1 (default).
    • 
        


        
Parameters
    
              
  • statebool 1 to enable auto-ranging, 0 otherwise.
    • 
        


        
This command enables or disables the auto-ranging feature for power measurement. When auto-ranging is active, the Powermeter compares the measured signal to the currently used measurement range. If the signal falls outside the optimal range, the Powermeter automatically adjusts the measurement range. Changing the measurement range will temporarily interrupt the measurement for up to 10 milliseconds to allow the analog hardware to stabilize. After this period, measurement will automatically resume.
 For continuous wave (CW) signals, the power auto-ranging feature automatically selects the optimal range for measuring your signal effectively. You can use the SENS#:POW:RANG? function to check the currently selected measurement range. When measuring modulated signals in CW mode, it is advisable to manually set the range using SENS#:POW:RANG to avoid the meter from permanently switching ranges.
 When using auto-ranging in peak mode, the input signal must consist of repetitive pulses with a pulse-to-pulse power difference of less than 5 percent. In this mode, the Powermeter automatically selects the appropriate range and adjusts the threshold for peak detection. If the signal is lost, the algorithm will initiate a peak-finding procedure after a timeout of 500 ms. For all other types of pulse signals, you will need to manually set the range using SENS#:POW:RANG? and adjust the threshold with SENS#:PEAK.
  The state of auto-ranging is stored persistently and will be restored after a reboot. If you change the sensor type, auto-ranging is enabled by default. You can check the ranging status by looking for flag bit 2 in the Operation Status register using the STAT#:OPER:COND? command to determine if the ranging pause is currenly active.

        
>> SENS:POW:RANG:AUTO 1

        
Auto-ranging in peak mode also changes the threshold value

        
For scope mode it makes sense to disable auto-ranging to get a seamless result stream.

        SOUR#:VOLT:CORR:SLOPSets the analogue output gain

      

      

        
SOURce
#
:VOLTage:CORRection:SLOPe[:OUTPut][:MAGNitude] 
<slope>

        
Suffixe
    
          
  • Sufix 1uint Analogue output channel from 2 to 4. Default 2.
    • 
        


        
Parameters
    
              
  • slopefloat,MIN,DEF,MAX new gain slope for given channel. MIN, DEF or MAX to set predefined values.
    • 
        


        
Use this command to set the analog output voltage conversion gain. The powermeter calculates DAC_V = Physical Unit * gain.  The unit of the gain depends on the selected analog output channel and the  connected sensor. For the calculation of gain check the voltage range of the selected channel by calling SOUR#:VOLT? or refer to the product manual.
 The following example illustrates how to select a suitable gain for a given application: Assume the maximum output voltage of the selected channel is 2V and the expected power to be measured is 3 mW. The ratio of maximum voltage to expected power is 2 V / 0.003 W = 666.66. To generate an output voltage of 1.5 V at 3 mW, a gain of 500 can be selected. Alternatively, a gain of 100 could be chosen to generate 0.3 V at 3 mW.
 The following channels are available for the analogue output: 
     
  • SOUR2: Generated power/energy DAC output slope. The unit is V/W for photodiode sensors, V/W for thermopilesensors, or V/J for pyroelectric sensors.
    •  
  • SOUR3: Beam X position DAC output slope. PM100D3 only! The unit is V/µm.
    •   
  • SOUR4: Beam Y position DAC output slope. PM100D3 only! The unit is V/µm.
    •  
  The gain is stored persistently and will be automatically applied after a reboot. 

        
>> SOUR2:VOLT:CORR:SLOP 1e-3

        
SOUR3 and SOUR4 are only allowed for PM100D3.

        
TLPMX_setAnalogOutputSlope(), TLPMX_setPositionAnalogOutputSlope()

        STAT:AUX?Queries the SCPI Auxiliary Event register

      

      

        
STATus:AUXiliary[:EVENt]?

        
Response
    
          
  • bitmaskuint 16 bit wide event register bit mask.
    • 
        


        
Use this command to query the SCPI 16-bit Auxiliary Event register bit mask. The Auxiliary register set provides a summary of the operating state of auxiliary equipment connected to the Powermeter.
  Reading this event register automatically resets its value back to 0. The content of the register is a bit mask, with a 1 bit for each event that has occurred since the last time the register was read. If the same event occurs multiple times, the event bit remains set to 1. To understand the meaning of each individual bit, refer to the description of STAT:AUX:COND?. The event register can capture changes in the Auxiliary condition register. The two transition registers are used to mask changes in the condition register to the event register. If a specific bit in the condition register changes from 0 to 1, and the corresponding bit in the positive transition register STAT:AUX:PTR is set to 1, the event register will also set that bit to 1. Similarly, changes in the condition register from 1 back to 0 can be detected using the negative transition register STAT:AUX:NTR, following the same logic.
 Changes in the event register can be summarized in bit 0 of the SCPI status register if enabled by STAT:AUX:ENAB. To read the SCPI status register, call STB?. After a reboot or after executing CLS, all events will be reset to 0.
 For more information about the SCPI register system in general, refer to the SCPI register set section.

        
>> STAT:AUX?
<< 253

        
Some events might get lost if same event occurs multiple times without the event register being read in between.

        
Reading the event register automatically resets register to 0. To get the events bit positions read STAT:AUX:COND?.

        
TLPMX_readRegister()

Response
