Use this command to query the SCPI 16-bit Auxiliary Condition register bit mask. The Auxiliary register set provides a summary of the operating state of auxiliary equipment connected to the Powermeter. The content of the register is a bit mask, with a 1 bit for each condition that is currently active. Please note that some conditions may only persist for a very short duration. In such cases, using the event register STAT:AUX? may be more appropriate. You can configure the positive STAT:AUX:PTR or negative STAT:AUX:NTR transition registers to map changes in the condition register to the event register. The following are the masked events:

    •  
  • bit 3: Customer calibration active. See SENS#:CORR:CSET#:STAT.
    •  
  • bit 5: Battery charging.
    •  
  • bit 6: Battery low.
    •  
  • bit 7: Bluetooth enabled. PM100D3 only.
    •

    •

 For more information about the SCPI register system in general, read the  SCPI register set section.

        STAT:AUX:ENABSets the SCPI Auxiliary Enable register

      

      

        
STATus:AUXiliary:ENABle 
<bitmask>

        
Parameters
    
              
  • bitmaskuint 16 bit wide bit mask for enable register.
    • 
        


        
Use this command to set the SCPI 16-bit Auxiliary Enable register bit mask. The content of the register is a bit mask, with a 1 bit for each enabled event that should be forwarded to bit 0 of the 8-bit SCPI status register. Refer to STB? for more information. To understand the meaning of each individual bit, consult the description of STAT:AUX:COND?. This enable register functions as a filter mask for all auxiliary events (see STAT:AUX?) that should be forwarded to the SCPI status register. If the enable mask is set with all bits as 1, bit 0 of the SCPI status register will be set to 1 whenever one or more events are triggered in the STAT:AUX? register.
 The purpose of this abstraction concept is to read the SCPI status register and monitor for changes in bit 0. When this bit changes, the user can then query the Auxiliary Event register to obtain the details. Modifying the enable register while active events are present may directly update the summarized SCPI status register bit.
 For more information about the SCPI register system in general, read the   SCPI register set section.

Ensure that the positive and negative transition registers are set accordingly to change the event register. Forwarding only works if event register gets updated.

        STAT:QUES?Queries the SCPI Questionable Event register

      

      

        
STATus:QUEStionable[:EVENt]?

        
Response
    
          
  • bitmaskuint 16 bit wide event register bit mask.
    • 
        


        
Use this command to query the SCPI 16-bit Questionable Event register bit mask. The Questionable register set monitors the validity of the measurement results.
 Reading this event register automatically resets its value back to 0. The contents of the register act as a bit mask, with each bit set to 1 representing an event that has occurred since the last time the register was read. If the same event occurs multiple times, the event bit remains set to 1. To understand the significance of each individual bit, refer to the description of STAT:QUES:COND?. The event register can capture changes in the Questionable Condition register. The two transition registers are used to mask changes in the condition register to the event register. If a specific bit in the condition register changes from 0 to 1 and the corresponding bit in the positive transition register STAT:QUES:PTR is set to 1, the event register at that bit position will be set to 1. It is also possible to detect changes in the condition register from 1 back to 0 using the negative transition register STAT:QUES:NTR, following the same logic.
 Using the event register is particularly useful for short-lived conditions, such as a brief peak causing an overflow of the measurement range. Changes in the event register can be summarized to bit 3 of the SCPI status register if enabled by STAT:QUES:ENAB. To read the SCPI status register, call STB?. After a reboot or after executing CLS, all events are reset to 0. You may want to adjust the data format of the bitmask using FORM:BASE.
 Read the SCPI register set section for more information about the SCPI register system in general.

        
>> STAT:QUES?
<< 253

        
Some events might get lost if same event occurs multiple times without the event register being read in between.

        
Reading the event register automatically resets register to 0. To get the events bit positions read STAT:QUES:COND?.

  • Hardware bit 9 (512 dec): Bandwidth output filter available

    •

    •

    •

    •  
  • Measurement bit 9 (512 dec): One time auto-ranging measurement mode supported
    •

  • System bit 4 (16 dec): Serial communication capability
    •  
  • System bit 5 (32 dec): Ethernet interface capability
    •  
  • System bit 6 (64 dec): Bluetooth Low Energy capability
    •  
  • System bit 7 (128 dec): Bootloader capability for firmware updates
    •  
  • System bit 8 (256 dec): External flash memory capability
    •  
  • System bit 9 (512 dec): JSON export capability for parameters and data
    •  
 
The Auxilary bits have the following meaning:
 
     
  • Auxiliary bit 0 (1 dec): Digital I/O capability
    •  
  • Auxiliary bit 1 (2 dec): External NTC (Negative Temperature Coefficient) sensor capability
    •  
  • Auxiliary bit 2 (4 dec): External digital sensor capability
    •  
  • Auxiliary bit 3 (8 dec): Customer-specific I2C interface capability
    •  
  • Auxiliary bit 4 (16 dec): Fan controller capability
    •  

        
>> SYST:CAP?
<< 1,29,1023,503,991,15

        SYST:ERR?Reads and removes oldest element of SCPI error queue

      

      

        
SYSTem:ERRor[:NEXT]?

        
Response
    
          
  • errorint SCPI error code. If no error occurred result will be 0.
    • 
          
  • errDescstring error code English description text.
    • 
        


        
This command checks for any errors that occurred during command execution or any asynchronous device errors. The device maintains an internal error queue to store SCPI errors. This command retrieves and removes the oldest entry from the queue. You should call this command multiple times until the queue is empty and the function returns 0, indicating "No error." Note that the internal queue has a limited length; if it is not regularly cleared, you may lose errors when the queue becomes full.

        
>> SYST:ERR?
<< -113,"Undefined header"

        SYST:FILE:READ?Reads block out of flash file system file

      

      

        
SYSTem:FILE:READ? 
<offset>
, 
<len>
, 
<asHex>

        
Parameters
    
              
  • offsetuint offset in file where to start reading. 0 for start.
    • 
              
  • lenuint amount of bytes to read. Need to be less than 200.
    • 
           
  • asHexbool Optional! 1 to return file content as hex string. Use 0 for binary files. Use 1 for text files (Default)
    • 
        


        
Response
    
          
  • filesizeuint size of file in bytes
    • 
        


        
Call this method multiple times after calling SYST:FILE:OPEN? initially to read a binary or text file content. You can randomly access the file at different offset to read blocks of the data. Use the optional asHex parameter for different output formats. Set to true for binary files and to false for text files to speed up file transfer.
 If asHex is set to true the response is a hex string with 2 hexdigits for every byte.
 If asHex is set to false the response will directly contain all printable characters. All non printable characters are escapted with a $. If the text contains $ it will be escaped as double $$. For closer details see this example response. Once all data has been read ensure to release all resources by calling SYST:FILE:CLOSE finally.

        
>> SYST:FILE:READ? 100,100
<< 106,]$0aThorlabs; PM62; 10 ms; 04.01.2000 01:51:37; CW; 3; C; PASS $0a$0a

        SYST:PARA:IMPO:JSONImports device parameters from JSON string

      

      

        
SYSTem:PARAmeter:IMPOrt:JSON 
<adapt>
, 
<jsonStr>

        
Parameters
    
              
  • adaptbool true to adapt parameters to ranges. False to generate error when out of range.
    • 
              
  • jsonStrstring device parameters as single line JSON format string. May be a substring of json line if larger 240 chars.
    • 
        


        
Use this command to re-import a previously stored parameter set. The command will parse the JSON input and apply the parameter values. To export a parameter set, use SYST:PARA:EXPO:JSON?. You can import parameters within the same sensor family; for instance, you can import parameters exported for one photodiode while another photodiode is currently connected. Use the "adapt" parameter to allow the command to modify parameters that are out of range. If adaptation is not permitted or if the input data is invalid for any reason, a SCPI error will be queued. Use SYST:ERR? to verify if the import was successful. 
 If the JSON input string exceeds 240 characters, the input data must be split into multiple calls of this command. The JSON fragment data will be buffered and reassembled in the device's memory. Once all data is transmitted (as determined by counting curly brackets), it will be parsed and executed. You can discard any buffered input data by sending the magic character #.

        
>> SYST:PARA:IMPO:JSON  1,'{"pm":{"name":"PM100D2","ser":1},"sens":[]}'

        
The maximal request length is limited to 240 characters! Call this command multiple times with sub strings.

:IDN?

        
Suffixe

Response

    •

Use this command to query the light sensor head identification. Next to the name, serial and calibration date you get 3 numbers. The following listing defines the sensor types: 
     
  • 1: Single photodiode sensor
    •  
  • 2: Thermopile sensor
    •  
  • 3: Pyroelectric sensor
    •  
  • 4: Four Quadrant thermopile sensor
    •  
 These are the sensor subtypes: 
     
  • 1: Adapter sensor without head correction.
    •  
  • 2: Sensor without head temperature sensor
    •  
  • 3: Sensor filter slider. (Photodiode only)
    •  
  • 18: Sensor with temperature sensor

 The sensor capability flags are a bitmask with a bit set to 1 if the sensor supports the following function 
     
  • bit 0(1 dec): Sensor supports auto-ranging

    •

    •  
  • bit 4(16 dec): Sensor has support measurement result accelerator. (For Thermopiles)
    •  
  • bit 5(32 dec): Sensor allows frontend bandwith limitation
    •  
  • bit 6(64 dec): Sensor allows peak measurement
    •  
  • bit 7(128 dec): Sensor allows frequency measurement
    •  
  • bit 8(256 dec): Sensor supports zeroing
    •  
  • bit 9(512 dec): Sensor allows setting tau
    •  
  • bit 10(1024 dec): Sensor can measure position
    •  
  • bit 11(2048 dec): Sensor can measure photometric results
    •  
  • bit 12(4096 dec): Sensor can measure head temperature
    •  
  • bit 31(268435456 dec): Sensor uses new bit mask format.
    •
